<p>Dear APSE member,</p>

<p>Here at APSE we are excited to partner in a research study carried out at the University of Massachusetts Boston and the University of Minnesota. This research study aims to improve the quality of employment services available to job seekers with intellectual and developmental disabilities (IDD).</p>

<p>I hope that you too will consider partnering with this project. You can help if your organization has at least three direct service staff who assist job seekers with IDD in finding paid individual employment. Please let the researchers know about your interest by filling out this short survey about your program. It will take less than five minutes.</p>

<p><a class="btn btn-primary" href="https://www.surveygizmo.com/s3/2458902/CRP">Take the survey</a></p>

<p>The information that you submit will help the researchers to identify eligible employment programs that represent diversity across a number of factors including job seekers' support needs, community characteristics, and support strategies. After submitting the survey, you can expect the following:</p>

<ul>
	<li>
	<p>If your program qualifies for participation—and you will agree to collaborate at that time—research staff will ask you to forward an invitation email to all direct service staff in your organization who work full time and who have at least one year experience supporting job seekers with IDD.</p>
	</li>
	<li>
	<p>The direct service staff will be asked to complete a baseline survey (15 minutes one time), four quarterly surveys (15 minutes each), and a daily survey for smartphones (one minute per day for a year). Overall the study is estimated to take about five hours total over the course of one year.</p>
	</li>
</ul>

<p>By partnering in this study, you will receive a final report of aggregated anonymous findings. You may find this information useful for determining effective employment support practices.</p>

<p>For more information about the study, please check the frequently asked questions listed below. If you have additional questions or any concerns, please contact Alberto Migliore, at alberto.migliore@umb.edu or at 617-287-4306.</p>

<p>Thank you, and we hope that you'll join us as partners in this research study.</p>

<p>Sincerely,</p>

<p>Allison Wohl<br />
APSE Executive Director</p>

